Oct 27 2008 	Value for money! Stay here!	My wife and I have just returned from a 7 night stay at The Orleans Hotel &amp; Casino. We are in our mid 30’s and have travelled quite a lot, including Las Vegas 3 years previously when we stayed at the Luxor. Here are my thoughts…We arrived at around 7pm on a Thursday evening and the check in queue was short and the line was quick. I tried the $20 trick (where you slip a $20 bill under your credit card as you pass it to the clerk for ID) and asked if there were any non smoking, high floor, recently remodelled rooms available with a good view of the strip. The clerk saw the 20, grew a big smile, took it like lightning, quickly glanced from side to side, and said that she would be sure she could find us something which we would be very happy with! Success! The room was fabulous, very big and spacious and exactly as I asked for with a great view of the whole strip (in the distance). First thing we noticed about the room was that there was absolutely no evidence of smoking. There was no stale smoke smell which was perfect, and the general cleanliness of the whole room was absolutely spot on. There were only about 7 coat hangers in the hanging area (sectioned off next to the bathroom) so I called housekeeping and asked for 10 more which were brought to our room within 15 minutes. Heading down to the casino for the first time was quite overwhelming as it’s a huge place. We wandered around to get our bearings, had a few drinks, and played loads of slots for a few hours. However, every time we sat down at a machine and touched the metal part we were getting a static shock. After about 50 of these I was getting really p*ssed off and decided to change my shoes thinking it may have been a footwear related problem. Nope, still getting them! Aaaaargh! This was to be the pain of our holiday – static shocks almost everywhere at every machine, in every casino! The only place where I didn’t get them so bad was in the Palazzo casino. Does anyone else get this? Or is it just my wife an I?! Anyway back to the review…We ate at Don Miguel’s restaurant on our first night which was pretty good. Usual standard Mexican food but the salsa (which came with the complimentary tortilla chips) was just the best tasting we ate anywhere in Vegas! There are a number of other restaurants and food places in the hotel but as we ate out most of the time, we only managed to try the Orleans French Market Buffet and Subway. The breakfast buffet was easily the best value for money that we found anywhere, and the quality was good. We ate breakfast most days here, apart from once at Planet Hollywood, where we found that the price difference was huge but the difference in quality and selection was only minimal. Stick with The Orleans buffet for breakfast and you wont go far wrong! Also, if you sign up for the Club Coast players card you will receive $5 worth of free slot play and a $1 discount per person each visit at the buffet, making it the best value breakfast eats available. Also with your Coast Card you get a 10% discount at the hotel shops including the gift shop.Back to the room again: the furniture wasn’t worn (as some reviewers have stated) and the yellow/gold patterned carpet looked quite new with only a few minor stains here and there. The artwork on the walls was good and colourful and there were lights and lamps everywhere! The seating area close to the big window was nice and we had a full size French style couch (finished with wood detailing) and an armchair to relax in. The large air conditioning unit worked great but woke us up during our first night as it’s quite noisy. Not being able to find an off switch anywhere, we called maintenance who came first thing the next morning. The guy told us to change the control panel setting to “economy” and this would switch the system off until you change the setting again to auto, slow or full. Problem solved! Some people on here have expressed disappointment with the walls being thin but I’m glad to say that we didn’t experience any problems with noise at all – not one bit! Once the door was closed we didn’t hear a peep from the next room either side nor from the corridor during the whole time we were there. A couple of things which my wife asked me to mention was that there is a small patterned window in the bathroom high above the end of the bathtub which you could open wide and let in some fresh air which was nice. Also she liked the fact that the cups in the bathroom were quality plastic cups which were single use (disposable) and sealed, so nobody had used them before. A coffee maker in the room with a range of different coffees and disposable Styrofoam cups was also a bonus.The distance to the room from the casino was easy and made a nice change - when we stayed at the Luxor previously it was about a 20 minute hike to the room from the casino which got really annoying after a few days. I’m glad to say The Orleans was completely the opposite. One reviewer on here mentioned that it was hard to find their room each time due to lack of directional signage. Again, we did not have this problem – there were more than enough directional signs and even a floor plan guide posted on the wall close to the elevators. Another thing, which a previous reviewer mentioned, was about getting dressed up for dinner. I must admit, I did experience what they said in that if you do dress up in your best stuff and look smart, then you will feel a little out of place sometimes in here. This is because most people at The Orleans wear casual stuff like shorts and t-shirt throughout their whole stay including on an evening.The pool was ok, but didn’t find it was anything to write home about. There were plenty of loungers and free towels available for guests to collect as you enter the pool area. 2 pools, one shallow kiddies pool and a larger main pool. The problem with this area is that the big hotel towers block the sun so there is only sun on the main pool itself for about an hour per day, no good for sun worshippers! This issue may have been increased because we were visiting in October when the sun is lower in the sky, I’m not sure. Another thing which was a little annoying was the plant area for the giant air conditioning chiller units which service the hotel was right next to the pool terrace, so you could hear a permanent constant noisy “hummmmmmmmm” throughout the whole area. Certainly not very relaxing when you want to chill out at the pool.Back inside the hotel’s hulking cavern of a casino, there were 5 separate bars (all very much the same) dotted around the casino floor, with the biggest one being in the middle next to the sports book with a small comfy seating area with tables to one side to enjoy a drink. The best thing about staying at The Orleans was that everything inside was very well priced. The bars all offered bottled beers for $1.50 and spirits with a mixer for $3.50. This is a world apart from buying drinks at some casino bars on the strip where you would easily pay at least $8 per drink. There was also a small cabaret lounge where there were live acts on nightly, mostly a band playing with a singer. An additional bar was located at Brendan’s Irish Pub which was over in one corner close to the buffet. Disappointingly it lacked theme and seemed just the same as every other bar in the casino. You could tell it was a kind of half hearted attempt at an Irish pub with a little wood panelling here and there but it was just a bit boring. Worse still, they killed it by having Karaoke on all the time which just drives people out! Never saw more than a few people in there. If you want to visit a real Irish pub, just next to the hotel across from the shuttle bus pick up point, is McMullen’s Irish Pub. We visited there and enjoyed some drinks in a lovely atmosphere and very authentic décor, just like in Ireland itself! The shuttle service to and from the strip was very convenient and was a great way to save money on paying inflated taxi fares. On the couple of occasions when we were unable to catch the last shuttle back from the strip at 12.30am, our taxi fare was around $14 inc a $2 tip. The shuttle was never full and ran every 15 minutes during the day and a little less often on an evening (probably about once every 20 mins). It was a quick service and the bus drivers sure know how to put their foot down and get you there quickly! The only small issue we had with this service was that it didn’t actually start until 9.30am. So some days when we wanted to be up and out early to the strip, we had to get a cab.Overall, yes The Orleans is predominantly a locals hotel and there are not a great deal of tourists here, but it’s a very, very affordable alternative to the sometimes extremely expensive strip hotels. It’s a great place to stay and I’m sure people would find it just as nice and if not better than a lot of the places on the strip. I mean, look at The Tropicana for instance – this place is the pits, it’s on it’s knees and is beyond refurbishment! The Orleans is ten times better, and way cheaper too! If you are looking for a hotel with loads of facilities, big clean rooms, a good theme, well priced food and drink, a huge casino with a wide choice of gaming, and a price which will not break the bank – then I’m sure you wont go far wrong with staying here. Enjoy!	
Oct 25 2008	Great as Usual	My son and I were at The Orleans Hotel from Oct. 8th -13th, 2008, and as always, we had a very enjoyable stay. I find it hard to believe that anyone would be dissatisfied with The Orleans. I have stayed at this hotel at least six times over the past several years, it's my favorite hotel in Vegas. The rooms are large, housekeeping is excellent, personnel are pleasant, restaurants are good, rooms are reasonable, video poker machines are generous, entertainment is great, and getting around the city is very easy with their free shuttle to the Strip. The only negative I can say is the area around Tropicana Avenue where this hotel is located seems to be going down, and I would not feel completely safe walking alone in the area. But, most of our time was spent inside the hotel or touring the Strip. Also, I went over to their sister hotel, The Gold Coast, and played bingo (transportation was provided free by the hotel shuttle). I find the reviewer's comments on an earlier post regarding bed bugs absolutely unbelievable compared to my experiences at The Orleans.	
