Jul 25 2008 	Another Good Stay at The Orleans	Great check-in. We were first in line. Had our room requests filled without a problem. Rooms are still nice and very clean. Had no problem parking in their garage on the first floor even on busy dates like July 4 and 5.The carpet in the hall outside the room did show a few stains. Have not seen that before. On July 4 and 5, although the hotel was nearly but not completely sold out, the elevators were quite crowded and sometimes you needed to wait for one. One time I had to wait for the 5th elevator. Ice machine was also out one day. No more coupon book at check-in. I asked and they have discontinued them.Buffet was great. Lines moved fast even on July 4 and 5. If you sign up (first time) for the players club (Club Coast), they will give you a coupon for a FREE breakfast or lunch buffet. You can instantly use it.Stayed 7/1-7/5. Paid $23.40 per night the first 3 nights and $61 on Friday, July 4 plus got a $50 gas card from Expedia. Would stay again. One week prior I stayed at the South Point Hotel which is newer and nicer rooms but a little further from the main strip vs. The Orleans.	
Jul 24 2008 	Unbelievably Good	Absolutely loved it here! Excellent hotel. Our original booking was for 9 nights (with five nights elsewhere) but we cancelled our other booking and stayed here for 14 nights instead as we liked it so much. Let me start off by saying that we paid $34 Mon-Thurs &amp; $80 Fri-Sun. For this price it is definitely an absolute gem – I still can’t get over the value for money. We will definitely be staying here again – it’s just fantastic. Included in the price was free use of the spa (steam room and jacuzzi) and gym (large and well equipped) free local calls from your room and free use of the internet at their business centre – amazing! There is mention of a $5 resort fee, but I think this is only charged if you book via a third party (ie expedia etc). We certainly were not charged it. The RoomOurs was a non-smoking King room. It was large and clean with an extremely comfortable bed and adequate pillows. The air con is noisy but effective (you soon get used to the noise) and I have to say, it is the quietest room I have stayed in in Las Vegas! We had an amazing panoramic view of the strip and were very close to the lift (which isn’t a bad thing as the hallways are LONG!!). Bathroom – large enough (small bath – I am a bath person &amp; I didn’t use it as it was very shallow) the shower was great though. NegativesIntermittent strange eggy smell coming from the sink – not very pleasant when you get a whiff of it – I think the cleaners try and cover the smell up by using grapefruit scented bleach – it masks the smell for a period of time then it comes back – wasn’t a huge problem and wasn’t evident all the time. There is no wardrobe in the room, only a rail beside the sink in the bathroom. Not a huge problem at all – just a strange layout really &amp; an odd choice given the amount of free space in the room – it could easily accommodate a standalone wardrobe. Tip, if you are staying a while bring some hangers – there were only about ten. The ShuttleDo not let the location of this hotel put you off staying here. It is a 7 minute shuttle ride to Bills Gaming Hall on the strip and the shuttles run every 15 mins or so and also stop at The Gold Coast (The Orleans’ sister hotel). It is SO convenient and it’s a pleasure to leave behind the chaos and crowds on the strip and come back to a wonderful hotel. This saved us an absolute fortune as we didn’t pay for taxis at all.The French Market BuffetAte here for breakfast, brunch (on Sunday) and lunch (didn’t try dinner). Oh My Gosh! I think it was something like $7 each for breakfast and $9 for lunch. On top of this you get $1 off per person for being a Club Coast Member! Me &amp; my partner had breakfast here daily and it was something like $13 plus tip. There was plenty to be had. We tended to go for cereal, fruit and yoghurt then a made to order omelette with bacon then a lovely dessert. There was loads of other stuff too. Unbelievable value for money and loads of choice – it kept us full till tea time!. I’m still missing this like crazy!!!! Lunch was a joy – carved hams, ribs, half a chicken, salads galore. They had four stations, Mexican, USA, Seafood and Chinese I think with various other items scattered about. The deserts were amazing and they had Mr Whippy style icecream – mmmmm. Put it this way, we stayed there 14 nights and didn’t get bored of the selection. We also tried TGI’s –which was perfectly fine – great burgers. I wasn’t impressed with Don Miguels Mexican restaurant (and Mexican food is one of my favourites) or the Courtside Café either – substandard food I thought. Didn’t get round to trying Terrible Mikes. Having a Subway on site was so convenient for late night snacks, quick bites etc. They also have a Seattles Best Coffee Shop and a Kates Corner for ice cream – both were wonderful and so CHEAP!!!!All the staff were so friendly and welcoming. After our first week the lady at Seattles Best knew my order by heart and the buffet staff kept seating us at our “usual booth”. Fantastic. CinemaThey have an 18 screen cinema on site – fantastic. We went there twice – saw Hancock (which was excellent) and Get Smart (which was pretty dire, but watch-able). It’s as good (if not better) than any cinema complex I have been to in the UK and the popcorn machine there was lovely. Bowling AlleyThey have a 70 lane (I think) bowling alley which we visited only once during our stay as they were holding a bowling competition for a lot of the time we were there. When we did visit my one complaint was that there is a very limited choice of bowling balls and a lot of them are chipped etc which makes it even more difficult to get a strike! Still it was fun and great to have it on site and, again, outstanding value for money. Poker RoomHas to be one of the best poker rooms I’ve seen. Extremely comfortable chairs all non-smoking. Excellent daily tournaments, very professional. They held their Orleans Open championship whilst we were there. This is held in their Mardi Gras Ballroom upstairs – it is HUGE. The tournaments were exceptionally well run and both me and my partner had good results here. I made a final table (finished 10th) and my partner won one of their regular tournaments winning $2,900 – not bad for a $200 entry fee. Overall a fantastic place to play poker. Some regular and good players and some regular not so good players!!! CasinoLarge, not overly smoky or that busy (save for July 4th weekend!) good atmosphere. Excellent craps tables (my only weakness where gambling is concerned, apart from poker) if you tip the cocktail waitress well for your first round they will keep coming back, so do it!!! The Pool I was very impressed with the pool area. Last year we stayed at The Rio which is renowned for its beautiful pool area. The Orleans comes very close to the Rio on a smaller scale. It’s a lot more peaceful too – great atmosphere and plenty of shaded areas. Loved it here – didn’t spend enough time out there!! Spa /Business Centre The spa was free to use and had steam room and Jacuzzi. Very quiet. Very nice changing room with free water and toiletries. It was a bit worn round the edges but pleasant nevertheless. The business centre consisted of four laptops I think with printing, copying and faxing facilities. Laptops were free to use and very convenient. We booked our Grand Canyon trip here and checked our emails. Very good perk of staying here and remember – it’s all free! BoozeThey have their own off-license – opposite TGI’s and the prices are amazing – much cheaper than duty free – tip for you – they sell “bubble wrap wine skins” at $2 each – these should protect any bottles you pack in your cases.What else can I say about the place – all being well we will be back next year. To put this review in context, we have been to Vegas three times before and we have stayed at The Rio once and the Wynn twice. When my other half first walked into the Orleans he wanted to walk straight out again, but after two days he was as taken with the place as I am and just like me, cannot wait to get back there next year. As a treat we actually spent one night at the Wynn (whilst keeping our room at The Orleans) and although it’s not fair to compare the two properties (they are in different leagues) we were happy to get back to The Orleans. Hope you enjoy your stay there. Get it booked while you can!!!	
Jul 13 2008 	A decent hotel/casino	I went to Las Vegas (for the first time) for a business trip, and had this hotel strongly recommended since the shuttle for the business I was visiting stopped here.Rates were very good, and the room was quite well furnished for the price. Bathrooms and linens were clean and the room was well lit. I didn't have a great view out my window, but the windows were nice and clean and I can't complain about that. Air conditioning worked well.The restaurants on-site were good. Service was friendly but slow at the on-site steakhouse, but dinner there was very good and made up for the wait.The hotel's credit card machines were down during my stay, so they were having some trouble processing charges and check-in was a bit slow. Check-out went much faster. I used the hotel's bell service to hold my bags for the last day of the trip and they did a fine and friendly job of it.This may not be the fanciest or the snazziest hotel in Vegas, but it is perfectly fine for the price and I would happily go back.	
Jul 11 2008 	A nice alternative to the Strip	On our recent trip to Vegas to visit family, we stayed at the Orleans for 4 days, then drove to Zion National Park for a few days, and returned to the Orleans since we were flying out of Vegas the next morning. This hotel was half way between our family's home and the Strip, so it was a decent location. The prices were less than on the Strip, especially during the weeknights. We never did use the shuttle to the Strip.The rooms are large, as were the pool and hot tub. The landscaping was nicely done for a &quot;value&quot; hotel. The only thing we didn't like about the room was the bathroom. There is no door between the tub/toilet and sink, so although the bathroom was very large and included closet space and room for luggage, it was not very private. One evening, a siren went off at about 2am. I believe it was on another floor but it was very loud and we heard it in our room. A recorded message kept broadcasting that the cause of the alarm was unknown. This went on for over an hour. My husband finally went down to the lobby to ask security about this. An unfriendly guard informed him that nothing was wrong and told everybody to go back to their rooms. Not very comforting! On the way back to the room, he ran into another guard who did tell him that the problem was a water pipe burst on another floor. I don't know why the alarm kept continuing, or why the guard at the lobby could not provide more information, but this put a damper on our stay.There are several restaurants here. We tried the Prime Rib Loft, which I found to be very good and reasonably priced. There is also a video game room, movie theatre and bowling alley on the premises, making this an ideal place for families.	
