Apr 30 2008 	Good for Vegas first-timers	I have been to Las Vegas numerous times, but this was my first and last stay at The Orleans. Immediately upon entering the hotel lobby, the smell of cigarette smoke was overwhelming. My eyes started burning and tearing up after just a few minutes. Check in was quick-about 5 minutes. I requested a quiet room and was accomodated. I proceeded to my room on the 19th floor (out of 21 floors). The hallway carpet was grossly stained. However, I was pleased because the cigarette smell subsided once I entered the elevator. The room was adequate- a good size for Las Vegas. It had a loveseat and 2 chairs. Thank goodness the bathroom has a small window that opens for fresh air. Without that, I would have checked out after the first night. There was a small coffeemaker and a safe. The tub was larger than normal.I ordered room service on my second day there. Big mistake! I routinely order room service at most hotels I stay at and this was by far the WORST. The chicken smelled bad. I took a few bites and it tasted as if it had been sitting in a warmer for 3 days. I soon got a stomachache and decided to only eat the baked potato and dump out the rest. I got the feeling they don't serve much room service.Some good things about the Orleans. Every staff person I came across-with the exception of the poker room-was pleasant and friendly. There is a free shuttle that runs every half hour to the strip and drops off across the street from Caesar's. This is a very good thing because when I took a cab from the strip -Mirage- I paid $15 before tip. The cab fare from the airport was $21. If you are renting a car it is fine to be off the strip. The food at the Orleans was cheap, but you get what you pay for. The spa is a nice addition. It has a sauna and jacuzzi. Also, internet access is free for 10 minutes daily. This allows you to print your boarding passes for your flight home. The hotel also has a movie theater and childcare center as well as bowling alley. I would only recommend this hotel for traveler's on a tight budget, who have never been to Vegas before and don't mind cigarette smoke. I definetely would not stay here with children.	
Apr 26 2008 	Good off-strip hotel choice	If you’re looking for an off-strip option to the Las Vegas experience, The Orleans is a good choice.I’ve been going to Vegas for years and have always stayed on a strip property. However, I’ve grown tired of trying to find tables with less than $15 minimums (especially on busy days/weekends), so on the suggestion of a family member, I decided to stay off-strip this time and after looking at reviews here and doing my own research, I chose The Orleans.It was a good choice and I just completed my second stay there in a month. The Orleans is located on Tropicana Blvd., about 2.5 miles west of the intersection of Tropicana and Las Vegas Blvd where the New York New York and MGM are located. It is NOT within walking distance of these locations, especially in summer. The Orleans offers a shuttle service that operates every 20-30 minutes and takes you from the Orleans to the Strip – it drops you off outside of Bill’s Casino on the strip when is across the street from Caeasar’s Palace. Anyway, I would recommend forgoing the shuttle. I was there in March and April and while it was not hot during those visits, I could see in the summer where waiting for the shuttle out in the heat (with no shelter to cover the sun) would be less than pleasurable. I took the shuttle once and it was OK – full, but I’m more of an instant gratification type of guy and didn’t like having to wait about a ½ hour each time (even though those timeframes are clearly posted by the hotel – so not their fault at all). It’s just so much easier to grab a cab and pay the $10 - $12 fare (includes tip) to the strip. Then do the same on the way back. But, the shuttle is a nice, clean option for those who do not want to use a cab.Check-in on both trips was very easy. Only a slight wait the first time and there was no wait this last time (Tuesdsay, April 22). On my first Orleans stay in March, however, I did notice a couple of times while gambling that there were quite long lines at check-in, but they seemed to be moving. Greeted with a smile and asking my room preferences both times. Both times they assigned me to a room exactly as I asked, including a high room, away from elevators.Rooms were clean, though basic and somewhat dated. But I wouldn’t expect more for the outstanding rates offered at the Orleans. This past stay, my rate was $49/night for 3 nights. I received a room with two queen beds, a small sofa, a chair and a desk chair, a desk with a chair and an armoir that held a 25” standard TV (not plasma or LCD) and room for most of your clothes. The bathroom is a little different. A sliding wood door is what separates the bathroom from the rest of the room and takes a little getting used to, but is otherwise functional. The bathroom set-up is very basic (like the room itself) but contains everything you need. The only thing that I would suggest to the Orleans regarding their bathrooms is to supply a soap dish to hold the used soap. It just feels very Motel 6ish when you have to put your used soap directly on the sink because there’s nothing else there to put it on… The water pressure in the shower was always fine and water temperature from very cold to scalding hot was always available. The shower even has a small window that opens slightly. Back to the living area – the beds are very standard, basic beds – which means either quite hard or quite soft. The comforters are dated (ugly, actually) and I strip them off the bed anyway before sitting on the bed for a number of reasons I’ll let you figure out. The pillows provided are totally insufficient and very uncomfortable. They are very small, routinely flat you receive two of these on a queen bed and three on a king size bed. You will want to call housekeeping and have them bring you at least two more. The carpet is garish (a yellow, red pattern), but seemed clean. All in all, if you are one to simply use the room as a place to sleep after a long day of gambling, eating and drinking, it’s just fine. If you’re looking for a little luxury because you spend most of your time in the room watching TV or reading, then you would probably want to stay somewhere else. For me, it’s perfect.The issue of the in-room safe: yes, they provide an in-room safe large enough to hold my laptop and several other items. The bad news – it is not secured to anything. It sits atop a shelf in the open closet area of the bathroom. I did use it, however, to hold my valuables since I had no other choice. It is a little disconcerting, though, to think that someone could simply walk up and rip the safe’s cord of the wall and walk off with it if they were so inclined. They really should bold those down to the shelves.Also, wireless internet connections are available in the rooms and the cost is $12.99 per 24 hours of use. The signal was strong and the connection was fast.Both times, my rooms were very quiet. I rarely heard neighbors and the noise from outside was minimal. The hallway carpets could use a good deep cleaning – stains were evident along the yellow edges of the carpeting in the hallways.Elevators were never a problem. Never had to wait long for one and they were never so crowded that it was uncomfortable.Good mix of all age groups represented at the Orleans. 20s and up. Very few kids. Music in the background on the casino floor is always ‘80s top 40 type of music – doesn’t stray much from that genre though. The place, for me, where the Orleans really shines is its’ customer service and casino area. Every employee I ran across greeted me with a “hello” and a smile. There is a security guard stationed near the elevators and they all had a smile and a “thank you” for showing your room card. Most of the dealers, bartenders, and cocktail waitresses are very friendly as well. The hotel has a really good restaurant selection (seven or eight of them) and I’ve eaten at all but a couple. I will alert you, first, however about the buffet. Each night is a “special” night and Wednesday nights is prime rib night. I might well have been the worst prime rib I’ve ever had. Very overcooked, tough and colorless. The remaining selections were merely average. Price was $15 and for the $15 you can get a much better meal somewhere else in the casino. In fact the prime rib at the Prime Rib loft was very good. I enjoyed the shrimp cocktail and Boston clam chowder at Big Al’s Oyster Bar and had a lunch special at Koji’s which was average. I ate many meals at their “diner” style restaurant called the Courtyard Café. Good selection at very reasonable prices and always good sized portions and quite good. Service at all restaurants was always very friendly and quick. No complaints at all with restaurant service there. There’s also a TGI Fridays inside when has it’s traditional menu.All in all, I will stay here again. It’s the best of both worlds for me. I avoid the crowds and noise of the strip, yet I’m close enough that a $10 cab ride gets me over to the strip (which I did a couple of times) if I want that vibe and energy (and other gambling options) and all at room rates that are generally excellent.	
Apr 25 2008 	Great deal!	Room:The room was really big with a view of the strip. The decor was slightly outdated and could have used a little bit of sprucing but overrall decent. However, the water coming out of the bathroom sink smelled like sewerage and we could smell it slightly in the room. There is internet access here but it is $12 per 24 hours. I did not pay it. Location:About 5 minutes off the strip but we got the room at a special rate of $30 per day so could not go wrong. There is a free shuttle that runs pretty frequently to and from the strip so no need for a car if you plan on staying close by.Casino:The casino is large with several restaurants and, of course, a buffet. We ate at the buffet once for dinner and once for breakfast. The buffet is a good value and offers a large variety of food. The quality of the food was very good.Pool:Large pool area with plenty of lounge chairs. There is no jacuzzi but there is a wading pool that is heated and has jets. Fitness room:The gym is nice. About 15 cardio machines and about 8-10 nautilus machines. Not bad at all for working off the calories from the night before's buffet. All the machines seem to be fairly new. There is also a nice spa but I did not use it. Overrall:If you are willing to stay off the strip this is a great hotel to consider. Look for a special deal on the room as we got our room for $30 per night (weeknights). This is not the Venetian or the Wynn but it's a great cost effective alternative.	
