Mar 30 2008 	Stayed at The Orleans	Good place to stay if you don't need immediate access to the glitz of the new or old strip. The fitness center/spa is top notch. It has a good work out room, good shower/locker accomodations, and best of all it's free! Most of the casino hotels in Vegas charge $10 to $20 for the fitness center. There is a shuttle to the new strip that seemed to be on an appropriately frequent cycle.Price: Attractive, I paid less than $100 at the last minute for a very busy Friday night. I saw a $56 rate for a weeknight.General look and feel: You will feel like you are staying in a less-glitzy, off the strip casino hotel. The furniture in the room has a worn look to it, but not bad. The housekeeping seemed good.Pool: Looked good, lots of kiddies though.Gaming area: Certainly serviceable gaming areas, the chandeliers in the gaming area are wild and cool looking. The sports book looked good.Eating: The buffet was one of the better I've had in Vegas when considering the cost, I think I paid $8 for a lunch buffet, and it had good variety and good layout to access the buffet bars.	
Mar 30 2008 	Great Rooms and Staff	Stayed here for 6 nights. The room was simple, but more than adequate - 2 queen sized beds and the love seat and chair area were great. There was enough room for 2 adults and 2 (active) children to not get into each other's space too much over 7 days. The staff was great - from the bell desk to the housekeepers, everyone was more than friendly and accomodating. The Kids Tyme child care was awesome - our children asked to go, as there was more than enough for them to do for a couple of hours and they made some new friends. You pay $7/hr ($6/hr for houseguests) per child, and they have VERY reasonably priced food the children can order (with their parents' prior consent) - all in all a better experience then taking them to the arcades or Adventuredome.I would recommend the hotel for its rooms; however the casino was less than generous to us and they often had machines down (the entire one and only Megabucks carousel was down for quite a bit of the day) and the craps tables were cold each time we checked, so we ended up gambling much less than we planned to. You need to drive to all other casinos, so, being that we were for the most part arranging our gambling time around our children's bed time (switching off, going downstairs one at a time), we were for the most part held hostage to the Orleans.	
Mar 29 2008 	Big and Clean Room Poor Housekeeping	My family of 3 stayed at this hotel for several days in March 2008. We drove to the hotel on Sunday at about 4 PM. It was easy to get to from the airport.  Unfortunately, there was no designated spaces for hotel guests to unload their luggage in front of the hotel. The valet guy told me that we could park by the curb at a spot across 5 lanes of cars from the hotel front entrance, and unload our stuff, but we had to give him our car key (in a sense, valet parking) unless at least one of us stayed with the car during our registering. I did not want to pay for valet parking just for registering and unloading our luggage, so I parked at the spot he pointed out, went inside the hotel myself to register while my wife and my son stayed in the car.  As soon as I entered the hotel, I smelled cigarette, which was stronger than I expected, because the registration counter is on the fringe of the casino area so that the smoke generated by smoking gamblers was distributed all through the ground floor. The cigarette smell was barely tolerable. Las Vegas appeared to be the cigarette smoking capital of the U.S. because every where I went on the ground floor of each of the Las Vegas hotels and the areas outside the Las Vegas hotels, I ran into people smoking.  I had to wait only 5 minutes for my turn to register inside the hotel. The woman who checked me in was friendly. AFter I had gotten my computer card room keys, I returned to our car, unloaded the luggage and told my wife and son to wait by our luggage outside the hotel. I then drove to park in the parking lot of the Orleans Arena next door to the hotel. I walked for about 8 minutes back to the front entrance of the hotel to meet my wife and son, and proceeded to our room with our luggage.  Both my wife and my son commented how strong the cigarette smell was in the &quot;lobby&quot; of the hotel. The elevators to the rooms were located about 5 minutes walk from the hotel front entrance, on the fringe of the casino. Thus, the Orleans Hotel is not as bad as the large hotels on the strip in terms of the distance from the hotel entrance to the elevators to go up to the guest rooms.  After getting off the elevator, it was quite a walk to our room because our room was near the end of a very long hallway. One thing I noticed was that there was no cigarette smell in the hallway and in our room, as if the living quarters and the ground floor casino were in two separate buildings served by two separate air conditioning systems.  When we walked from the elevator to our room, I saw that the carpet lining the hallway had obvious stains in a number of areas showing that the carpet really need to be replaced. But we were happy with the cleaniness of our room. We were given a strip-view non-smoking standard room with 2 queen size beds. The room was very big. Having stayed at a number of hotels in both coasts, I would rate this room to be the biggest standard hotel room we have stayed at. The view of the strip also was nice.  However, the brass collar of the lamp next to the window was broken. I informed housekeeping of the problem and they said they would send an engineer to fix it. We went out for dinner. We did not eat at the hotel that night. But several people we knew ate at the buffet restaurant at the hotel that night and told us that the food was not very good. When we got back to our room that evening, I saw that the engineer had put a paper tape around the broken brass collar of the lamp to hold it up. If I were the engineer, I would have replaced the lamp or at least fixed it with an insulating plastic tape. Being very tired, I did not complain to housekeeping about the quality of the repair, figuring that we were just staying for several days. I merely told my son to not touch the lamp.  My wife took her shower and told me that the bath tub did not drain water very well. Because we were too tired to call houskeeping, we went to bed. The beds and pillows were average in terms of comfort, but the bed sheets were too small for queen size beds. The air conditioner was rather noisy. But we got used to it quite soon and fell asleep without any trouble. The next morning, I took the shower and found that the water rose to about half an inch above the bath tub drain during the shower so that there was a pool of water where my feet were. The water was hot enough and the water pressure was quite good. After the shower, I called down to housekeeping complaining about the water drainage problem and they said they would send an engineer to fix it. I put $3 in an envelope marked &quot;House Keeper&quot; next to the TV and we left for sight seeing. When we returned that evening, the bath tub drainage problem had not been fixed. In addition, the housekeeper did not replace the plastic water cups and the paper coffee cups that we had used. I called housekeeping complaining about the water drainage problem again and told them to send an engineer the next day to fix the problem.  The second morning, I once again left $3 for the house keeper and went out for sight seeings. When we returned, the drainage pproblem stayed the same and the water cups and coffee cups were not replenished. I called housekeeping complaining about the drainage problem again. The person who took my call recognized my voice and said that she would write a big note for the engineer about it. I requested that she sent the engineer the following day to fix the problem.  We went downstairs to meet up with 4 people we knew for dinner at the Prime Rib Loft (sort of on the second floor of the hotel) without any reservation at about 7:30 pm. Because the Prime Rib Loft was connected to the casino without any wall, I noticed that the cigarette smell in the Prime Rib Loft was stronger than that in the casino. It might be because cigarette smoke rose in the air so that the smoke was more concentrated in the loft than in the casino downstairs. The hostess told us that there was no open table for 7 at that time and we would have to wait till 8:45 pm for the next table. With the cigarette smell being as strong as it was, we did not want to dine there.  Instead, we went to Canal Street downstairs. Canal Street was a restaurant inside the hotel at the fringe of the casino area. Because Canal Street was connected to the casino with a closed door, the cigarette smell inside Canal Street was much lighter than that in the casino area or the registration area. We had prime ribs and sea bass, which were very good. The service also was good.  The third morning, I did not leave any money for the house keeper because I was not happy with the house keeper's repeated failure to replenish the cups in our room. We went out for sight seeing again. When we returned later that afternoon, I found that the drainage problem stayed the same. The situation was worse than the last two days in that not only did the house keeper not replenish the cups, she also did not leave us with a fresh roll of bathroom tissue. Because I did not notice the lack of bathroom tissue until the fourth morning, I called housekeeping and told the staff only about the unfixed drainage problem and the lack of water cups. She offered to send an engineer up right away. But I told her to not bother because we were checking out the next day anyway. I told her that if I were to do my job the way the hotel engineers did theirs, I would have been fired long time ago. She also wondered how their engineers do their jobs. I told her I needed water cups. She said she would send someone to bring us new water cups. When we returned to our room after dinner, we saw a stack of about 10 precious, plastic water cups in our room. Finally, at least one of my complaints resulted in a resolution of a housekeeping problem. But before my stay at the Orleans Hotel, I did not know that plastic water cups could be that precious. When I got up the fourth morning at about 7:30 AM, I noticed that the house keeper did not leave us any fresh roll of bathroom tissue. My patience was running out, I called housekeeping and demanded that someone bring us bathroom tissue. She said someone would bring us the tissue shortly. But it was not until about 8:10 AM before a woman brought us two rolls of bathroom tissue.  At 8:17 AM, somebody knocked at our door. I recognized that it was a house keeper because every morning at about that time in the past several days, a house keeper (not the same one every morning) had knocked at our door. I could not figure out why the house keepers wanted to wake hotel guests up so early every morning. May be they were too anxious to get the rooms clean early so that they could go home early. But with patience running out concerning housekeeping of the Orleans Hotel, I opened the door and asked the house keeper what she wanted. She did not dare to tell me that she wanted to clean my room at that moment. She also did not apologize either. She just walked away and knocked at the door of the room next to us. I poke my head out in the hallway, raised my voice at her and said: &quot;It is only 8:17 AM, for god sake!&quot; She looked at my direction with an facial expression that told me that she most likely did not understand what I was saying. To not waste time, I closed my door, took my shower and packed for our trip home. The check out went smoothly. I only had to wait 3 minutes for my turn at the check out counter. In my opinion, the Orleans Hotel definitely has housekeeping problems. But if all you want is a hotel at a low rate, and you are willing to put up with the housekeeping problems, I think the Orleans would work for your stay at Las Vegas. Its room size and low rate could not be beated by any strip hotel. Our room was cleaner than some rooms we stayed at in some 3-star hotels across the country.	
Mar 27 2008 	Everything the strip has at 1/2 off	I booked my room directly with the hotel from an email I had received from Clubcoast. The bed was king size and very comfortable, the heat and air conditioning are controlled by a thermostat that you set for the desired temperature. I had a room overlooking the pool, it was spacious and quiet. I paid $30 for 1 night on Easter Sunday. The casino has everything that all of the Strip hotels have. The property has several different restaurants, I did not dine here so I will not comment on the food. Friendly staff and the rooms were clean and in good working order.	
Mar 24 2008	Fab Stay	We have just returned from a 7 night stay at the Orleans and have thoroughly enjoyed it.This was our first time in Vegas. Check-in was very quick, I asked for a high floor with a strip view and was very fortunate to be placed in a huge room on the 15th floor with fab views of the strip especially at night. The room had 2 queen beds which were very comfy and a 2 seater sofa, chair and coffee table.The bathroom was very spacious, had a shower over the bath and was very powerful. The standard of cleanliness was exceptional. The towels were large and fluffy and the complimentary toiletries were of a good standard. The room was very quiet and we never heard other guests.TIP-Always place the &quot;Do not disturb&quot; sign on your door otherwise the maids knock you up at 7am to clean the room!.The shuttle bus was great, very frequent and drops off at the side of Bills gambling hall which is about the middle of the strip. We never waited more than 10 mins . The facilities in the hotel were more than adequate. The $5 daily resort fee (per room) includes 30 mins internet access (in the business centre nr reception) however I ewas on much longer somedays and no one ever said or charged me anything! and free use of the gym, and free local telephone calls.The choice of eating places within the hotel are good. We ate at the Courtyard Cafe and it was very good. We only played the slots as we dont have a clue about gambling! The cocktail waitresses were much more frequent in taking orders in the casino in the Orleans than any other casino we visited.The pool area is really well kept and a lovely relaxing environment, and provides free towels. Only residents can enter the pool area.Security guards are always sat by the lifts and no one can get up to the guest rooms without showing their key card.There is a great shop within the hotel where you can purchase toiletries, gifts, and snacks as well as alcohol at terrific prices. A chilled bottle of decent rose wine was only $4 !On the morning of check-out (which is 12.00) we left our luggage with the bell boys and ate lunch in the hotel before stepping outside to take a cab back to the airport, there are always cabs waiting.We absolutely loved the Orleans and saved approx £200 by not staying at a strip hotel. It was nice to get away from the noise and hustle and bustle of the strip.	
Mar 24 2008 	Great Value Great Rooms	I head to Vegas about every six months, and haven't stayed at the Orleans in over 5 years. My mom was visiting me over the holidays, and we decided to head to Vegas for a few days. I usually like to stay at a different place each time, but with a tight budget being the holidays and all, we decided to go cheap. At $25/night (off season) I thought I'd try the Orleans again. I don't remember ever having a bad experience there before, but just prefer to stay on strip. Everything about it was perfect. The rooms were big, comfortable, and very clean. The wait staff was very attentive, and my drink was never empty. The bartenders were friendly, and bar drinks were not overly priced (like the on strip casino bars). There are plenty of choices for meals, with several restuarants.The shuttle runs every 30 minutes, and stops midstrip. I actually found when taking taxis back to The Orleans it is cheaper than staying in a strip hotel because the cab drivers use all back roads, and the Orleans is located mid-strip, but off-strip, almost a direct shot from anywhere on the strip.It was November, so the pool was cold, but, the pool area and hot tub open, which I really appreciate because I like to sit outside and read during the daytime (&quot;recovering&quot;). All-in-all I am very impressed with The Orleans, would recommend it anyone visiting Vegas.	
