Jan 12 2008 	Good value - large rooms	I was already in Las Vegas at a condo and needed to stay 1 more night. The Orleans had a great rate for the 1 night I needed. The room was large. Nice decor. But don't expect anything like Wynn's. I have stayed at most of the hi end hotels on the strip. This was above average for the price paid. The room itself was very clean. No noise. No smell of smoke. Housekeeping provided extra linens on request. The front desk people were friendly and helpful. When I made the reservations I was told of the resort fee. They made it very clear. I asked if the fee could be waived and they said no. At the front desk there is a sign posted advising of the $5 resort fee. The fee included use of pool, business center, free local and toll free numbers, and in room coffee. All A-list hotels on the strip charge about $1 per call for phones. Internet was free at the business center. I used the unlimted local calls for dial up internet access. I do not condone the resort fee and always ask that it be waived. The buffet is average for low budget buffets. I ate at Sahara buffet earlier in the week and it was about the same. The prime rib in the dining room was good. The in room coffee is not Starbucks quality. The machine was new and did require running many cups of water thru to eliminate the plastic taste. The coffee itself does not seem to be hi quality. For comparision, the coffee in most Marriott Hotel rooms is better, but still no where near Starbucks. If you want a good cup of coffee, go down to the lobby and buy Seattle Best. The cost for SBC in the hotel is above the street price. I have found that to be the case in all the hotels. The hotel provides transportation to the strip, but the wait can be long. It is much better to have a car if staying here. In summary, I found the hotel to be pleasant and a good value and would recommend staying here.	
Jan 6 2008 	Great Value	Great hotel off the strip. Plenty of parking fairly close to the hotel (no long walks). We were only there for one night but are actually returning again next week (business trip). Rooms are very large with either a king bed or 2 queens. Rooms also have a separate sitting area with sofa, chair, &amp; coffee table. Our room was on the third floor facing the strip so we had a decent view. Floors above the 5th or 6th floor would probably be even better. Beds are comfortable, pillows are small so we asked for a couple of extra ones (no problem). One minor problem is that our room had the standard &quot;straight&quot; shower curtain rod instead of the newer curved ones. Did not use internet access in the room but it appeared to be the wired type and overpriced in my opinion.Had dinner in the buffet and it was good. We will probably skip it this next trip and just go out to a local's restaurant for dinner. It's good, it just tends to cause you to overeat.Did not gamble on this very short trip but the casino seemed nice. Did not use the spa, fitness center, or pool area this trip.We have previously stayed at the Sun Coast Hotel in Vegas which is another sister property located in Summerlin (@ 8 miles from the strip). Both are great properties.	
Jan 6 2008	The Orleans: Great Value but maybe not on New Years Eve.	Stayed at The Orleans for 4 nights beginning on New Years Eve. This is a great location for the price. It is not right on the strip, but they provide a shuttle to the Strip every half-hour until 12:30 am. However, NOT ON NEW YEARS EVE. Vegas blocks off the strip for a giant street party on New Years Eve so the last shuttle is about 5:30 pm. If you stay at The Orleans on New Years Eve you need to plan on leaving the property early for the Strip. After about 6 pm a taxi cannot even get you close. Also, it is almost impossible to get a taxi after the fireworks. The Orleans has many excellent places to eat at a budget price. The rooms are large and the staff is very responsive. We had a problem with the sink and called for maintenance. They showed up almost immediately to fix it.I did not like the Poker Room, however, because they clearly cater to a large group of regular players. In their tournaments they rake off a portion of the entry fee to pay a $100,000 prize to the best poker player of the season. Unless you play there 3 or 4 times a week for several months you will not qualify for this award.I will stay there again, but not on New Years Eve.	
