Nov 28 2007 	Great Value and Service	I booked this hotel on a Sunday at $30.00 including tax. You can't go wrong there. There is $5.00 resort fee, but even this is petty for the price. That includes local phone calls (who uses a hotel phone these days anyway) and the business center, which I did use. The hotel is west of the strip, nothing really there, but they have a shuttle to the strip or you can drive. All the casinos have free parking. Check in was very quick and they gave me a large, beautiful non-smoking room facing the strip. The room was very clean, which many amenities, such as soaps, lotions, etc. There is a safe in the room also. I got myself a casino card and got a free lunch buffet, which was very good. I am not a big gambler, so I don't think I will use it to get comps, which come at $1.00 for each thousand points. The casino was quite big, but stunk from smoke. If you want to save money and don't have to be on the strip, then the Orleans will work for you	
Nov 28 2007 	Good value nice casino	We stayed 2 nights at the Orleans as part of a 7 night stay in Vegas (coming from New Zealand we wanted to experience so stayed Downtown, off-strip and on the strip).The Orleans was an excellent choice. Nice sized room, security for rooms at night, good casino and nice food choices (loved the clam chowder in Als Oyster Bar - the buffet was only okay). Think the resort fee is a farce but I was still happy with the deal and we would definitely return.Shuttle was a bit of a problem on one occassion - half the people waiting could not fit on and had to wait. We hired a car and visited Valley of Fire and the other off-strip casinos so we didn't need to use the shuttle on the second day thankfully.	
Nov 27 2007 	Good choice	I chose to stay at this hotel as I was attending concerts in the showroom &amp; am very glad that I found out about the place.The rooms are large, clean &amp; well equipped. They include a room safe, hair dryer, coffee machine, dressing area, clock/radio, sitting area with sofa &amp; armchair. The queen size bed was comfy &amp; the linen was of a good quality.There are a number of eating places in the hotel of various prices &amp; styles-the buffet is particularly good value.There is a gift shop which also stocks sandwiches &amp; snacks.The casino area is large &amp; there are plenty of machines/games for the &quot;low rollers&quot; who just want to play 1, 5 or 10 cents.It is a little distance from the strip but the shuttle bus does go regularly &amp; drops off at Bill's (Barbary Coast as was). There is also a city bus costing $1.25 which stops near the MGM. I found the hotel quiet at night (although if there was an event at the Arena this may change).Even if you are not a gambler I would suggest you obtain a Coast Club card. It costs nothing &amp; only takes a few minute to arrange, but you receive one free buffet &amp; $1 off all meals in the French Market.The $5 resort charge is something of a nonsense &amp; I would prefer they just upped the room rate, but that is a very small quibble against what is a very nice hotel.	
Nov 25 2007 	Best Deal in town	I don't travel without checking out Trip Advisor. This time we were looking for a inexpensive hotel and a nice one too. The Orleans is definately a winner! The rooms were large and beautiful. The pool and spa were relaxing. The gaming was awesome! No problems getting to the strip, there is a free shuttle from the Orleans to the Barbary Coast. If you want to go to Palms or Rio, the shuttle takes you to the Gold Coast also.. just walk across the street. So the fact that the Orleans is off the stip DOES NOT MATTER! The Orleans ROCKS!!! I won over $100.00 on the penny slots too... Have stayed here 2 times, and anytime we come to Vegas, we will be staying here... I LOVE THE ORLEANS!	
Nov 25 2007 	Well worth the price I paid	Stayed only one night on a stop over to another destination. However, I would have stayed longer and would more than likely return.For the record, I generally don't book top notch accomodations. I generally look for a place thats clean, decent, respectable and safe. This was all of them. I would much rather spend on other things than a room you spend little time in. This is a full service place with a couple of places to eat, coffee shop, fitness center, outdoor pool and an adjacent arena where you can catch big name shows. The casino is about the largest I've ever seen. Booked it on Hotwire in which you indicate a location and they pick it for you. I paid $42 plus the $5 resort fee. However, even at $47 it was a great deal. Room was clean and very big for a standard room. Twice as large as most other hotel rooms I have stayed in. Casino is huge and the hotel is large. They have a free shuttle to the strip which takes about 10 minutes so its totally worth it. I would have stayed longer if it was possible. Far exceeded my expectations considering Hotwire picked it and I really went into it blindly. Also, its close to the airport and the rental car pick up/drop off. If you are looking for low key value, this is it. If you are looking for more of a resort experience, this may not be for you.	
Nov 25 2007 	We have always liked this place however.........	we agree with 'ploughman8' that the hotel should just increase their rate by $5/night rather than try to schmooze guests into thinking they are paying for extras. The in-room coffee consists of two 6 oz individual servings of coffee. How many guests are going to be satisfied with that?? One other amenity the 'resort fee' covers is the fitness center. This is something for which I would not willingly pay extra. I do not visit Vegas to spend time on a treadmill. I can't even recall what the third insignificant item is covered by the resort fee.Orleans isn't the only hotel that tacks on a 'resort fee'. Sunset Station also does this. It leaves some guests feeling they've been slightly ripped off. If they would just increase the price by 5/night, people likely wouldn't give it a second thought.	
Nov 25 2007 	Price was right	Stayed on a Mon-Weds. Room was $35.00 a night. Check in was less then 5 minutes. Room was clean. There was a $5.00 &quot;resort&quot; fee which covered local calls and a few other minor things. The &quot;resort tax&quot; was posted in at least 2-3 places near the check-in so it wasnt a surprise. Off strip location on Tropicana, during the week traffic was crazy, and the mile or so drive to the strip between 4-7 pm frequently took 20 mins or so barring no accidents. I would not use any of the gas stations/restaurants in the vicinity of the hotel for safety reasons but the hotel property itself appeared safe and quiet. I had no contact with hotel staff other then checking in. Overall if I could get the room for under 50.00-60.00 a night I would surely stay there again. I would recommend the hotel to others.	
Nov 24 2007	Enjoyed the Orleans again!	We just came back from a couple of nights at the Orleans. We had not stayed there for a little over a year and I was a little concerned with some of the more recent negative reviews. However, I was once again pleased with the Orleans. Our room was nice and didn't seem like it was getting run-down as others as mentioned. They did charge the $5 fee but I was prepared for that. We actually like to use the spa there for the steam room and whirlpool on at least one afternoon. That and the fact that we only paid $35 a night and that made the room $40 did not mean a lot to us. So don't be put off! We also had no difficulty with the shuttle.	
Nov 23 2007 	Charges $5 a day resort fee. Be aware.	Booked the Orleans through a Travelocity special at $25/night for a couple of not-so-busy weeknights in November. It was a pretty good deal overall, though soured somewhat by the hotel charging a $5 a day RESORT FEE for all rooms. This supposedly covers in-room coffee, use of the fitness center and a couple of other minor things, none of which I used. Travelocity did not disclose this fee specifically, but I'm sure they've got some blanket disclaimer saying it's a possibility (as Priceline does). While I realize that it might still be a decent deal at $30+ taxes, this kind of practice by places like the Orleans really deserves pushback from travelers. Otherwise the hidden add-ons will only become more numerous (remember &quot;energy surcharges?&quot;), more costly, and will reach the point where rate quotes over systems like Travelocity become so irrelevant to what you really pay that they're just a form of bait-and-switch. It's also patently unfair to other hotels in Travelocity that play it straight and DON'T charge hidden fees like resort fees, as their offerings should get better play because of a cheaper all-in price but don't. This encourages the more-honest operators to lower their standards and adopt others' bad practices &quot;to be competitive.&quot; That's how these things fester. If the Orleans really needs the extra money, then it belongs in the base rate. As for the hotel, the rooms are basically OK even though some are far from the elevator bank. The casino used to be one of the best places in town to play Pai Gow poker, but they've upped the table minimums to $10 and I didn't see any $5 tables anymore. If you have your own rental car and can get a rock-bottom rate they might be worth considering (just be warned with the resort fee). However, if you're flying in and don't have a car and are there when rates are higher, it may well not be the best value.	
Nov 21 2007 	Great Value off the strip	If you can book early enough, you can get rates below $65 during the week. It's a few blocks east of the 15 but it's relatively simple to get back, and they provide a shuttle too.&quot;Chinatown&quot; is only a few blocks north of the hotel so that's a plus too if you're looking for plenty of asian restaurants (good and cheap too!) nearby.Service at the hotel is friendly and prompt. Dealers are friendly too - it's pretty cozy as the table floor space isn't that expansive. If I can't find a relatively cheap room on the strip next time, I wouldn't hesistate to return.	
Nov 21 2007 	We like The Orleans	We've stayed at The Orleans a number of times and we have always enjoyed our stays. The Orleans is roughly one-half mile off of the Las Vegas Strip and the pace is a little slower and we like that. The rooms at the Orleans are immense. The price is a bargain; we paid $35 a night for a Monday and Tuesday in November. The rooms aren't as glitzy as those on &quot;The Strip&quot; but we're okay with that. The casino has all of the games and services of the bigger casino and usually has smaller table stakes. The facility has nine restaurants, a movie theater and bowling. When we tired of gambling we went bowling and had a great time. If you want to go to the strip you can take the hotel's shuttle - it leaves every half hour. We like the fact that you can easily drive to and from The Orleans without the craziness of The Strip.	
